align=\"top\" | {{convert|171.50|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Woodville|suffix=, New Zealand}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|-40.3449|175.8676|format=dms}}\n| [[:File:Woodville railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the town of Woodville.\n|}\n\n===Private sidings===\nCurrently the only private sidings in use are Jukken Nisho at Waingawa and Fonterra at Pahiatua. The sidings remain at Taratahi but the main line points were removed around 2003 (Ravensdown Fertiliser). Lime Works at Mauriceville are also still connected to the network but are overgrown and covered with lime.  The former siding at Eurocell (Parapine) in Upper Hutt closed in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=WILLIAMS |first1=COLIN |date=1 February 2012 |title=Eurocell site sold off |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/local-papers/upper-hutt-leader/6345145/Eurocell-site-sold-off |format= |department= |newspaper=Upper Hutt Leader |type= |location=Upper Hutt |publisher=Fairfax New Zealand |publication-date= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=27 June 2014 |ref= }}</ref>\n\nExtensive sidings at Petone, Naenae (where the goods shed remains, in non-rail use), Taita (Unilever) and Trentham (Army) have been closed and removed. Other former sidings include one used by oil companies between Renall St and Masterton stations; disused sidings at Mauriceville and Eketahuna; the Ngauranga Industrial Siding to an abattoir in the Ngauranga Gorge; and a siding to the [[Featherston Military Camp]] north of Featherston during World War I.\n\n===Tunnels===\nNine tunnels have been constructed on the various routes of the Wairarapa Line. Of these, only three are now in use for railway purposes, and only the Wiwaka tunnel in northern Wairarapa (150m; between Mangamahoe & Eketahuna) has remained unaffected by deviations since the line opened.\n\nFive of these tunnels are now part of the Rimutaka Rail Trail: Mangaroa, Pakuratahi, Summit, Siberia and Prices. The Rimutaka Incline Railway project hopes to incorporate these tunnels into its restored railway line across the Rimutaka Ranges.\n\n====Original route====\nFrom Wellington to Woodville:\n* Cruickshanks Tunnel (120m) \n* Mangaroa Tunnel (152m)\n* Pakuratahi Tunnel (73m) \n* Summit Tunnel (584m) \n* Siberia Tunnel (108m) \n* Prices Tunnel (98m) \n* Wiwaka Tunnel (150m)\n\n====Current route====\nFrom Wellington to Woodville:\n* Maoribank Tunnel (572m)\n* [[Rimutaka Tunnel]] (8,798m)\n* Wiwaka Tunnel (150m)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Wairarapa Connection]]\n* [[Hutt Valley Line]]\n* [[Palmerston North - Gisborne Line]]\n* [[Te Aro Extension]]\n* [[Pahiatua Railcar Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book | last = Bromby | first = Robin | title = Rails that built a Nation: An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand Railways  | publisher = Grantham House | date = 2003 | location = Wellington | isbn = 1-86934-080-9  |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book|last=Cameron|first=Walter Norman|title=A Line Of Railway: The Railway Conquest of the Rimutakas|location=Wellington|publisher=[[New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society]]|date=1976|ISBN=0908573006|ref={{sfnref|Cameron|1974}}}}\n* {{Churchman & Hurst Railways of New Zealand}} pages 151\u2013162.\n* Leitch, David and Brian Scott ''Exploring New Zealand's Ghost Railways'' 2nd ed., Wellington: Grantham House, 1998, pp.&nbsp;39\u201343.\n* Mahoney, J.D. ''Kings of the Iron Road'' Palmerston North: Dunmore Press, 1982, pp.&nbsp;81\u201388.\n* {{cite book|last1=McClare|first1=G J|last2=Thomson|first2=R G|title=Wairarapa Railway Memories|publisher=[[New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society]]|date=1995|ISBN=0-908573-67-7|ref={{sfnref|McClare & Thomson|1995}}}}\n* ''New Zealand Railway and Tramway Atlas'' 4th ed., Exeter: Quail Map Company, 1993\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.valleysignals.org.nz/tunnels/cruickshanks.html |title=Cruickshanks Tunnel |accessdate=2007-09-05 |work= }}\n* [http://www.valleysignals.org.nz Valley Signals]\n\n{{Wairarapa Line stations}}\n\n{{NZR Lines}}\n\n[[Category:Railway lines in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in the Wellington Region]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1874]]\n[[Category:3 ft 6 in gauge railways in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1874 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{For| rail passenger services between Wellington and Masterton|Wairarapa Connection}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| logo                            = \n| name                            = Wairarapa Line\n| image                           = Woodside railway station 06.JPG\n| image_width                     = 250px\n| caption                         = [[Woodside railway station, New Zealand|Woodside railway station]]\n| type                            = Secondary line\n| system                          = \n| status                          = Open for passengers and freight\n| locale                          = [[Wellington Region|Wellington]] [[Regions of New Zealand|region]]<br>[[Manawatu-Wanganui]] [[Regions of New Zealand|region]]\n| start                           = [[Wellington railway station|Wellington]]\n| end                             = [[Woodville railway station, New Zealand|Woodville]]\n| stations                        = 27 current\n| routes                          = \n| daily_ridership                 = 679,455 trips annually (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gw.govt.nz/assets/Transport/Regional-transport/Wairarapa-Corridor/BackgroundandissuespaperWairarapaCorridorforconsultation.PDF|title=Wairarapa Corridor Consultation|publisher=[[Greater Wellington Regional Council]]|accessdate=21 December 2011|date=October 2009}}</ref>\n| open                            = 14 April 1874 (to [[Lower Hutt railway station|Lower Hutt]])<br />15 December 1875 (to [[Silverstream Bridge railway station|Silverstream Bridge]])<br />1 February 1876 (to [[Upper Hutt railway station|Upper Hutt]])<br />1 January 1878 (to [[Kaitoke railway station|Kaitoke]])<br />12 October 1878 (to [[Summit railway station, New Zealand|Summit]])<br />16 October 1878 (to [[Featherston railway station|Featherston]])<br />14 May 1880 (to [[Woodside railway station, New Zealand|Woodside Junction]])<br />1 November 1880 (to [[Masterton railway station|Masterton]])<br />14 June 1886 (to [[Mauriceville railway station|Mauriceville]])<br />10 January 1887 (to [[Mangamahoe railway station|Mangamahoe]])<br />8 April 1889 (to Eketahuna)<br />18 March 1896 (to [[Newman railway station|Newman]])<br />3 May 1897 (to [[Pahiatua railway station|Pahiatua]])<br />11 December 1897 (to [[Woodville railway station, New Zealand|Woodville Junction]])<br />\n| close                           = 28 February 1954 (Melling to Manor Park deviated)<br />21 November 1954 (Haywards to Silverstream deviated)<br />30 October 1955 ([[Upper Hutt railway station|Upper Hutt]] to [[Featherston railway station|Featherston]] deviated)\n| owner                           = [[KiwiRail]] (infrastructure)<br />[[New Zealand Railways Corporation]] (land)\n| operator                        = [[Transdev Wellington]], [[KiwiRail]]\n| character                       = Urban, provincial, rural\n| stock                           = [[New Zealand DF class locomotive (1979)|DFT class locomotive]]s<br />[[New Zealand FP class electric multiple unit|FP/FT class \"Matangi\" EMU]]<br />[[New Zealand British Rail Mark 2 carriage|SW/SE class carriage]]\n| linelength                      = Currently {{convert|171.5|km|mi}}<br>Originally {{convert|186|km|mi}}\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = Double (Wellington\u2013Trentham)<br/>Single (Trentham\u2013Woodville)\n| gauge                           = {{RailGauge|3ft6in|lk=on}}\n| electrification                 = 1500 V DC Overhead<br>14 September 1953 ([[Wellington railway station|Wellington]] to Taita)<br />23 November 1953 ([[Petone railway station|Petone]] to Lower Hutt)<br />24 July 1955 (Taita to [[Upper Hutt railway station|Upper Hutt]])\n| routenumber                     = WRL\n| speed                           = \n| elevation                       = \n| map                             = \n}}\n{{Wairarapa Line}}\nThe '''Wairarapa Line''' is a secondary railway line in the south-east of the [[North Island]] of [[New Zealand]]. The line runs for {{convert|172|km}}, connects the capital city [[Wellington]] with the [[Palmerston North - Gisborne Line]] at [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]], via [[Lower Hutt]], [[Upper Hutt]] and [[Masterton]].\n\nThe first part of the line opened in 1874 between Wellington and Lower Hutt, with the entire line to Woodville completed in 1897. It was the only [[New Zealand Railways Department|New Zealand Government Railways]] route out of Wellington until 1908, when the government bought out the [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company]] who owned and operated the present [[North Island Main Trunk]] section between Wellington and Palmerston North. The line originally included the famous [[Rimutaka Incline]], which used the [[Fell mountain railway system]] to cross the [[Rimutaka Range]] between Upper Hutt and [[Featherston, New Zealand|Featherston]]. In the mid-1950s, the line between Petone and Featherston was substantially realigned, with the line diverted to the east of the Hutt River between Petone and Haywards to serve new housing developments in northern Lower Hutt, and the construction of the [[Rimutaka Tunnel]] to replace the Rimutaka Incline. Part of the former route west of the Hutt River has been retained as the [[Melling Branch]].\n\nThe southern portion of the line between Wellington and Upper Hutt is electrified and is also known as the [[Hutt Valley Line]]. [[Transdev]] on behalf of the [[Greater Wellington Regional Council]] runs suburban services along the Hutt Valley section, as well as the [[Wairarapa Connection]] service between Wellington and Masterton. [[KiwiRail]] runs regular freight services along the line between Wellington to Masterton and between Pahiatua and Woodville. No regular services currently run along the Masterton to Pahiatua section, and this section is currently under review as part of [[KiwiRail#Turn-around plan|KiwiRail's turnaround plan]].\n\nThe [[Sixth Labour Government of New Zealand#Transport and Infrastructure|Labour government]] promised during the 2017 election campaign to upgrade the track to improve operation of the [[Wairarapa Connection]], and on 9 October 2018 the minister [[Phil Twyford]] announced that the proposed $196 million for the region included $96 million for the Wairarapa Line; $50 million in the Wairarapa and $46.2 million south of the Rimutaka Tunnel including double-tracking the Trentham to Upper Hutt section. Work is to start in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/rail-upgrades-big-win-wairarapa |title= Rail upgrades a big win for the Wairarapa |publisher= The Beehive |date= 9 October 2018}}</ref> The double-tracking will be completed in 2021. Other \"infrastructure renewals\" on the line include three bridges with timber elements and track renewal (including in the Rimutaka Tunnel) but no signals renewal. Passing loops at Carterton and Woodside had previously been removed, leaving Featherston with the only loop between Upper Hutt and Masterton; the Carterton loop may need reinstating at some time for more frequent trains.<ref>''Wellington Timetable Changes and Infrastructure Upgrades'' by Bruce Taylor in ''The New Zealand Railway Observer'' June\u2013July 2018 No 349, Volume 75 No 2 pages 62,63</ref> The \"infrastructure spendup\" announced on 30 January 2020 included passing loops at Carterton, Featherston and Maymorn and a second platform at Featherston but not the proposed hybrid trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/119129227/new-hybrid-trains-for-wellington-snubbed-in-government-transport-package |title= New hybrid trains for Wellington snubbed in government transport package |publisher=  Stuff (Fairfax) |date= 30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nProposals for railed transportation out of Wellington were made as early as the start of the 1850s, barely a decade after European settlement of the area began. In 1853 and 1857, investigation of horse-hauled [[tramway (mineral)|tramways]] was undertaken, but no action was taken. [[Robert Stokes (politician)|Robert Stokes]], a member of the [[Wellington Province|provincial government]], proposed a railway over the Rimutakas in 1858 and finally succeeded in gaining government interest in 1863. The Wellington Provincial Government established a committee to investigate proposals, and on 2 July 1866 it passed the Wellington, Hutt and Wairarapa Railway Ordinance.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nzlii.org/nz/legis/wgn_ord/whawro1866437/ |title= Wellington, Hutt and Wairarapa Railway Ordinance, 1866 |publisher= New Zealand Law online |date= 1866 }}</ref> The act authorised a railway employing either {{RailGauge|3ft6in|lk=on}} or {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}} to carry 200 tonnes at speeds of {{convert|24|km/h}}, but construction did not commence as sufficient funds were not available in the fledgling New Zealand colony, nor were they successfully raised in [[England]].\n\nIn 1870 [[Julius Vogel]] included a Wellington-Wairarapa railway in his [[Vogel Era|Great Public Works Policy]] and visited [[London]] to arrange a loan to finance the policy. On this trip he was approached by several contracting firms and a contract that included the first section of the Wairarapa Line was awarded to [[John Brogden and Sons|Brogden & Sons]]. The construction of the line can be considered in three stages: the [[Hutt Valley]] section, the route over the Rimutakas, and the line through the Wairarapa via [[Masterton]] to [[Woodville, New Zealand|Woodville]].\n\n===Hutt Valley section===\n{{further|Hutt Valley Line}}\n\nOn 20 August 1872 construction of the Wairarapa Line began with the turning of the first sod at [[Pipitea Point]], the site of Wellington's first railway station. Construction was delayed due to the difficulties associated with building a railway along the narrow, rocky shoreline of [[Wellington Harbour]], and the section to [[Lower Hutt]] was not opened until 14 April 1874. Further difficulties were encountered in building the rest of the route up the Hutt Valley along the [[Hutt River, New Zealand|Hutt River]]'s western bank, including the need to divert the river and reinforce its bank in places. On 1 February 1876 the line opened to [[Upper Hutt]].\n\n===Rimutaka section===\n[[File:Fell Engine Museum - 2002-03-20.jpg|left|thumb|One of the special locomotives employed on the Rimutaka Incline, [[NZR H class|H 199]], now preserved at the [[Fell Engine Museum]].]]\n\n{{further|Rimutaka Incline}}\n\nThe Rimutaka Range posed a severe difficulty to those involved in planning and constructing the Wairarapa Line. On 1 January 1878 the Hutt line opened to [[Kaitoke railway station|Kaitoke]] at the western foot of the range, and a steep but manageable route with a grade of 1 in 39-40 was found from Kaitoke up the [[Pakuratahi River]] valley to the site of Summit station, {{convert|348|m}} above sea level. However, from Summit down the eastern slope to [[Cross Creek railway station|Cross Creek]] near [[Featherston railway station|Featherston]], a gradient of 1 in 14-16 was required. This was far too steep for regular [[steam locomotive]]s to handle, and accordingly the Fell mountain railway system was employed. This used a centre rail to which specially-designed locomotives and brake vans clung, allowing them to climb the steep slope upwards or control the descent. Despite the terrain, construction of this unique route was completed swiftly, opening to Featherston on 12 October 1878.\n\n===South Wairarapa section===\nConstruction from Featherston to Masterton across the Wairarapa plains north of [[Lake Wairarapa]] was relatively easy. The decision was taken to bypass [[Greytown, New Zealand|Greytown]] and build the line through [[Woodside, New Zealand|Woodside]] to bridge the [[Waiohine River]] at a point far enough up the river to be considered safe; a line through Greytown would have required a bridge at a point considered unsafe by the surveyors. The [[Greytown Branch]] was constructed from Woodside, and Greytown was briefly the effective terminus of the Wairarapa Line from the opening of the branch on 14 May 1880 until the bridging of the Waiohine a month later. Later in 1880 the line opened all the way through to Masterton.\n\n===North Wairarapa section===\nThe northern Wairarapa was more rugged and isolated, and construction was slower and more difficult. [[Mauriceville, New Zealand|Mauriceville]], {{convert|20|km}} north of Masterton, was reached on 14 June 1886, followed by the next {{convert|6|km}} to [[Mangamahoe]] on 10 January 1887. The {{convert|10|km}} between Mangamahoe and [[Eketahuna]] included the {{convert|150|m|adj=on}} long Wiwaka tunnel, the only tunnel between the Rimutaka Incline and Woodville, and the section was opened on 8 April 1889. Construction of the {{convert|4|km}} section to [[Newman, New Zealand|Newman]] was inexplicably slow, not completed until 1896. [[Pahiatua]] was reached in May 1897, including the [[Mangatainoka River]] bridge, the longest bridge on the line at {{convert|162|m}}. Mangatainoka is {{convert|24|km}} from the bridge and the railway reached it in August 1897, and the line was finally opened to Woodville and a junction with the [[Palmerston North - Gisborne Line]] on 11 December 1897.\n\n===Branch Lines===\nFour [[branch line]]s diverge from the Wairarapa Line: the [[Melling Branch]] and the [[Gracefield Branch]] to [[Hutt Workshops]], both still open; the [[Greytown Branch]], closed in 1953, and the [[Hutt Park Railway]], which ceased serving its intended purpose in 1906 but survived in truncated form as an [[Rail siding|industrial siding]] until 1982.  At one time a branch line to [[Martinborough Branch|Martinborough]] was proposed but this line never eventuated.\n\n==Deviations==\nSeveral upgrades and alterations to the Wairarapa Line have been made, but only the Western Hutt and Rimutaka tunnel deviations have significantly altered its route.\n\n===Hutt deviation===\n{{further|Hutt Valley Line|Melling Branch}}\n\nIn 1925 construction began on what was then known as the '''Hutt Valley Branch''', leaving the main line just north of [[Petone]] station and running east to [[Waterloo, New Zealand|Waterloo]], opening on 26 May 1927. After [[World War II]], new [[state housing]] suburbs developed north of Waterloo, and the railway was extended to serve them. In 1954 it re-joined the western line south of [[Manor Park, New Zealand|Manor Park]] and superseded the old route. On 1 March 1954 the former Hutt Valley Branch became part of the Wairarapa Line and the western route was truncated into the [[Melling Branch]] from Petone.\n\n===Silversteam deviation===\nThe deviation included a new bridge across the Hutt River, replacing a section of line now used by [[Silver Stream Railway]]\n\n===Rimutaka deviation===\n{{further|Rimutaka Tunnel}}\n\nThe Rimutaka Incline was difficult, costly and time-consuming to operate, but as the Wairarapa Line had become a secondary route since the acquisition of the Wellington and Manawatu Railway in 1908, its replacement was not a priority. Various alternate systems and routes were debated, with a tunnel chosen in 1936. However, the economic conditions left from the [[Great Depression]] followed by the impact of World War II meant that work on the tunnel did not start until 1948. The Incline and the line up the western side of the Rimutakas closed on 29 October 1955 and the tunnel opened on 3 November 1955.\n\n==Operation==\n\n===Passenger services===\n{{main|Wairarapa Connection}}\nWhen the full line opened in 1897, passenger services from the Hutt Valley to Wellington were augmented by NZR's first express from Wellington, the [[Napier Express]] (the WMR had operated the Wellington-[[Longburn]] portion of the [[New Plymouth Express]]). After the acquisition of the WMR, the Napier Express was re-routed to the quicker west coast route in early 1909 and the [[Wairarapa Mail]] was introduced to provide a regular service through the Wairarapa to Woodville. In 1936, [[NZR RM class|RM class]] [[NZR RM class (Wairarapa)|Wairarapa]] [[railcar]]s were introduced; these were designed to operate at speed over the Rimutaka Incline and provided a much quicker service to Wellington and local Wairarapa services. They originally augmented the Wairarapa Mail but replaced it in 1948. Carriage trains operated only at peak times of the year when the railcar capacity was exceeded; in 1955, the Incline's closure meant the Wairarapa railcars were withdrawn and [[NZR RM class (88 seater)|88 seater railcars]] were introduced, boosting capacity at off-peak times. One Wairarapa railcar has survived and is currently under restoration by the [[Pahiatua Railcar Society]]. [[Mixed train]]s also operated until the 1950s.\n\n[[File:Electric Locomotives Near Paekakariki.jpg|left|thumb|EW 1805, which operated on the Hutt Valley Line. It survived for preservation and is seen here with [[NZR DC class|DC]] 4611 near [[Paekakariki]] on the [[North Island Main Trunk Railway]].]]\n\nIn the 1950s the Hutt Valley line was electrified using the 1500 V DC system already operating to [[Johnsonville, New Zealand|Johnsonville]] and [[Paekakariki]]. The electrification was opened to [[Taita, New Zealand|Taita]] on 12 October 1953 and Upper Hutt on 24 July 1955, allowing for a more intensive suburban commuter service to Wellington. Originally operated by [[NZR DM class|DM/D class]] [[electric multiple unit]]s and carriage trains hauled by [[NZR ED class|ED]] and [[NZR EW class|EW class]] electric locomotives, the carriage trains and many of the DM/D units were phased out upon the introduction of the [[NZR EM class|\"Ganz-Mavag\" EM/ET class]] units in the early 1980s. The [[New Zealand FP class electric multiple unit|\"Matangi\" FP/FT class]] was introduced on the Hutt Valley Line in 2011\u201312, initially relegating the Ganz Mavag units to peak services only before being completely replacing them from 2015.\n\nProposals have been made to extend the electrification into the Wairarapa and the Rimutaka Tunnel was constructed to allow overhead lines to be installed, although before opening diesel operation was adopted. In 2007, the Greater Wellington Regional Council rejected a call for the line to be electrified to Masterton, stating that patronage was too low to justify the capital expenditure.<ref name=\"electric\">{{cite news |last1=Farmer |first1=Don |date={{date|July 12, 2007}} |title=Wairarapa rail won't go electric |url=http://www.times-age.co.nz/news/wairarapa-rail-wont-go-electric/980824/ |work= |location=[[Masterton]] |publisher=[[Wairarapa Times-Age]] |publication-date=12 July 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415103820/http://www.times-age.co.nz/news/wairarapa-rail-wont-go-electric/980824/ |archive-date={{date|April 15, 2012}} |access-date=21 December 2011 |ref= }}</ref>\n\nRailcar services were withdrawn in 1977, and carriage trains were re-instated progressively from early 1964. Until 1963, a railcar service operated on Friday evenings between Masterton and Woodville, and in December that year the decision was taken to replace the morning railcar to Wellington with a carriage train as over 200 passengers wished to use the railcar service that had a capacity of just 176. The final railcar service was replaced by carriage trains in December 1977; some of the carriage trains from this point until the mid-1980s were made up of de-motorised former 88-seater railcars known as \"[[NZR RM class (88 seater)#Grassgrubs|grassgrubs]]\" in [[List of NZ railfan jargon|New Zealand railfan jargon]]. Passenger services through the lowly populated northern Wairarapa survived due to the poor roads in the area, but as they were improved, demand for the trains declined. Masterton \u2013 Palmerston North passenger trains ceased from Monday, 1 August 1988{{sfn|Bromby|2003|p=40|ps=&nbsp;\"Passenger services on the 80.5 km Masterton\u2013Woodville section ended from 1 August 1988\"}} with the last such service running on Friday, 29 July.{{sfn|Churchman & Hurst|2001|p=160}} In the 1990s, the service between Masterton and Wellington was rebranded as the [[Wairarapa Connection]] and presently operates five times each way weekdays (with a sixth service in the evening on Fridays), and twice each way on weekends and public holidays. In 2007, eighteen new [[New Zealand British Rail Mark 2 carriage|SW class]] carriages were introduced to replace the [[NZR 56-foot carriage|56ft carriages]] used since the service's inception; in 2013, they were joined by the six SE class to relieve capacity constraints especially on evening services.\n\nThe 2020-2021 ($300 million) Wellington Metro Rail Upgrade work started in November 2019 and is expected to take eighteen months. The single-track Trentham-Upper Hutt section is to be double-tracked, and will be equipped for bi-directional signalling so that trains can run on either track in either direction between Upper Hutt and Trentham (and possibly later to Heretaunga). The work is expected to improve the operation of both suburban passenger trains to Upper Hutt and the [[Wairarapa Connection]], with a longer loop at Upper Hutt to hold Wairarapa log trains.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Wellington Rail Upgrades|journal=The New Zealand Railway Observer|date=February\u2013March 2020|number=359|p=251\u2013252|volume=76| issue = 6}}</ref>\n\n===Freight services===\nUntil the acquisition of the WMR in December 1908 all NZR freight out of Wellington was carried on the Wairarapa Line. As soon as the western route became available, all freight that could be diverted off the Wairarapa Line was diverted, due to the difficulties created by the Rimutaka Incline. This meant that even some traffic from the northern Wairarapa was sent through the [[Manawatu Gorge]] and down the west coast to Wellington. The opening of the Rimutaka Tunnel made the line more desirable for through freight traffic, but as localised freight gave way to containerised inter-city freight in the 1980s, the significance of the Wairarapa Line declined, especially on the section north of Masterton.\n\nKiwiRail is currently investigating a log shipment hub in Masterton that would mean log traffic would use the northern portion of the Wairarapa Line, from Masterton to Napier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/5442814/KiwiRail-in-talks-to-revive-Wairarapa-rail-line|title=KiwiRail in talks to revive Wairarapa rail line|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011|author=Matt Stewart|publisher=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012 it was reported that the total freight carried on the northern section of the line had increased from 74,031 tonnes in 2009 to 97,139 tonnes in 2011, although this figure was inflated by a ten-day closure of the Manawatu Gorge section of the railway line due to a slip.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/6374796/Pahiatua-rail-link-looking-up|title=Pahiatua rail link looking up|publisher=[[Manawatu Standard]]|date=8 February 2012|accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nPresently freight services operate at each end of the line. Log and other wood-related traffic is moved between Wellington and [[Waingawa railway station|Waingawa]], just south of Masterton, with one overnight and one daylight return service on weekdays, and a daylight service operates both weekend days. Two freight trains operate from Palmerston North to Pahiatua and return on weekdays, the first in the early hours of the morning and the second in the afternoon. No freights currently operate regularly at weekends.\n\nKiwiRail ceased running timetabled revenue services on the Masterton\u2013Pahiatua section of the line in February 2015, transferring the Sunday Wellington to Palmerston North via Woodville run to the NIMT.  However, they have undertaken to keep it open and maintain it to an operational standard, in part because it is still in use by heritage operators,<ref name=\"Line to Pahiatua stays open\">{{cite news |last1=Yong |first1=Alisa |date=3 June 2015 |title=Line to Pahiatua stays open |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/wairarapa-times-age/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503414&objectid=11458882 |department= |newspaper=Wairarapa Times-Age |location=Masterton |publisher=NZME. Publishing |publication-date= |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=3 June 2015 |ref= }}</ref> particularly the [[Pahiatua Railcar Society]] and [[Steam Incorporated]].\n\n===Rolling stock===\n<!-- Commented out: [[File:E66 Petone Workshops 1906.JPG|left|thumb|E 66 at Petone Workshops in February 1906, just after it was built.]] -->\n\nIn the late nineteenth century, the first members of the [[NZR K class (1877)|K class]] to operate in the North Island were transferred from the [[South Island]] to work the Napier Express. They were augmented by members of the [[NZR M class|M]] and [[NZR N class|N]] classes. In the twentieth century, typical locomotives included members of the [[NZR A class (1906)|A]] and [[NZR Ab class|A<sup>B</sup>]] class. The Rimutaka Incline was almost always operated by the six members of the [[NZR H class|H class]] built specifically for it. In 1906 [[NZR E class (1906)|E 66]] was built for the Incline but did not prove as successful as the six H locomotives and was retired in 1917.\n\nWhen the Rimutaka Tunnel opened in November 1955, the Wairarapa Line became the first in New Zealand to be fully [[dieselisation|dieselised]] as steam locomotives were unable to pass through the tunnel. Initially, [[NZR DE class|DE]] and [[New Zealand DG and DH class locomotive|DG]] class diesels were employed, and they were soon joined by the [[New Zealand DA class locomotive|DA class]]. Until 1967, the Wairarapa Line was the only way DA class locomotives could access Wellington due to tunnels south of Paekakariki being too small. In the 1980s, the DG class had been fully withdrawn and the DA class in the process of withdrawal or conversion to the [[NZR DC class|DC class]]; accordingly motive power on the Wairarapa Line changed. Until 2015, the DC class was the mainstay of the Wairarapa line south of Masterton, with locomotives of the [[NZR DBR class|DBR]], [[New Zealand DF class locomotive (1979)|DF/DFT]] and [[New Zealand DX class locomotive|DX]] classes occasionally used. In July 2015, the DFT class took over services on the line.<ref>{{cite news |first= Emily |last= Norman |date= 2 July 2015 |title= Faster locos mean timely rides - council |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/wairarapa-times-age/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503414&objectid=11474493 |publisher= [[Wairarapa Times-Age]] |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2016, rolling stock regularly used on the Wairarapa Line include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n! Class\n! Image\n! Type\n! Cars per set\n! Number\n! Operator\n! Routes\n! Built\n|-\n| [[New Zealand FP class electric multiple unit|FP/FT]]<br />''Matangi''\n| [[File:NZR FP class 01.JPG|120px]]\n| [[Electric multiple unit|EMU]]\n| 2\n| 83\n|[[Transdev Wellington]]/[[Public transport in the Wellington Region|Metlink]]\n| Wellington suburban services (Wellington\u2013Upper Hutt)\n| 2010\u201312, 2015\u201316\n|-\n| [[New Zealand British Rail Mark 2 carriage#SW class|SW]]\n| [[File:Metlink SW 3394 at Masterton Station.JPG|120px]]\n| [[Passenger car (rail)|carriage]]\n| 6\u20138\n| 18\n|[[Transdev Wellington]]/[[Public transport in the Wellington Region|Metlink]]\n| Wairarapa Connection services (Wellington\u2013Masterton)\n| 1971\u201375\n|-\n| [[New Zealand British Rail Mark 2 carriage#SE class|SE]]\n| \n| carriage\n| 6\n| 6\n|[[Transdev Wellington]]/[[Public transport in the Wellington Region|Metlink]]\n| Wairarapa Connection services (Wellington\u2013Masterton)\n| 1971\u201375\n|-\n| [[New Zealand DF class locomotive (1979)|DFB]]\n| [[File:DFT KiwiRail.jpg|120px]]\n| [[diesel locomotive]]\n| \n| 5\n| [[KiwiRail]]\n| Wairarapa Connection services (Wellington\u2013Masterton) <br /> Wellington\u2013Masterton freight\n| 1979\u201381\n|}\n\n===Signalling===\nThe Wairarapa line used four of the six [[New Zealand]] [[railway signalling]] systems: ''[[Double line automatic signalling|Double Line Automatic (DLA)]]'', ''[[Centralised Traffic Control|Centralised Traffic Control (CTC)]]'', ''[[Track Warrant Control|Track Warrant Control (TWC)]]'' and Station Limits. Signalling at Petone is future-proofed for conversion to a fifth system, Automatic Signalling Rules (ASR).\n\nThe Wairarapa Line had a number of lasts for railway signalling in New Zealand\n* [[Railway semaphore signal|Semaphore Signal]] on an operational line, these were decommissioned in 1996 however the masts (poles) remained in place until July 2014.\n* Line controlled by ''[[Tyers Electric Train Tablet]]''\n* Manned signal box outside of a major station\n\nPrior to the Trentham\u2013Upper Hutt\u2013Featherston section being transferred to Train Control in February 2007, this was the last section with CTC controlled by a [[signalman (rail)|signalman]]. Part-time signal boxes remained at Petone (weekday peak and inter-peak) and at Taita (weekday peak) until December 2013 and July 2014 respectively, when signalling was switched to Train Control in central Wellington.\n\nMasterton is a unique signalling arrangement with Track Warrant Control ending at 'TWC Ends' boards north of the two-position home signal, which allows shunting movements to be carried out without the need for a Track Warrant. Along with [[Horotiu railway station|Horotiu]] (on the NIMT between Te Rapa and Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia) Masterton still has Woods Points Keys. The Horotiu ones are not in regular use.\n\n==Heritage==\n[[File:Carterton Railway Station 02.jpg|left|thumb|[[Carterton railway station]], base of the Wairarapa Railway Restoration Society Inc.]]\n\nSeven [[Railway preservation in New Zealand|railway preservation]] organisations are based on or close by the Wairarapa Line.\n\n===New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society===\n{{Main|New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society}}\nNZRLS has a workshop based at the northern end of the [[Silver Stream Railway]] where members restoring two [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company]] carriages. It also has an archives building beside [[Ava railway station]] in Lower Hutt.\n\n===Silver Stream Railway===\n{{Main|Silver Stream Railway}}\nThe [[Silver Stream Railway]] is a heritage railway in Silversteam, Wellington.\nIt regularly operates preserved [[New Zealand Railways Department]] locomotives along a restored section of the [[Hutt Valley Line]] (part of the Wairarapa Line), deviated in 1954.\n\n===Rimutaka Incline Railway Heritage Trust===\n{{Main|Rimutaka Incline Railway Heritage Trust}}\nThe [[Rimutaka Incline Railway Heritage Trust]] is based at [[Maymorn railway station]] and its ultimate goal is to return the Rimutaka Incline to full operational condition as a tourist attraction.\n\n===Fell Engine Museum===\n{{Main|Fell Engine Museum}}\nThe [[Fell Engine Museum]] is a short walk from [[Featherston railway station|Featherston station]] and includes preserved H 199, the sole Fell steam locomotive ([[NZR H class]]) left in the world. The museum also has a Fell brake van and other railway-related items of historical significance.\n\n===Woodside Station Preservation Society===\nThe Woodside Station Preservation Society focuses its activities on the [[Woodside railway station, New Zealand|Woodside railway station]] Building.\n\n===Wairarapa Railway Restoration Society===\n{{Main|Wairarapa Railway Restoration Society}}\nThe [[Wairarapa Railway Restoration Society]] focuses its activities on the [[Carterton railway station|Historic Carterton railway rtation]] complex, which includes a museum inside Carterton's historic station building, [[rolling stock]] in the station [[rail yard|yard]], and other heritage items.\n\n===Pahiatua Railcar Society===\n{{Main|Pahiatua Railcar Society}}\nThe [[Pahiatua Railcar Society]] is at [[Pahiatua railway station]], which is no longer served by passenger trains but maintained by the society. It has the only surviving Wairarapa and 88-seater railcars and is restoring them to operational condition; it also has an operational [[NZR RM class (Standard)|Standard railcar]].\n\n==Features==\n\n===Stations===\n{{main|List of Wellington railway stations}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=5 |\n\n====Wellington Section====\n|-\n! Distance from Wellington\n! Name\n! Location\n! Image\n! Notes\n|-\n| {{n/a}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Te Aro|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|17|30.28|S|174|46|54.47|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | Terminus of the Te Aro Extension from 1893 to 1917.\n|-\n| {{n/a}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Lambton|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|16|42.52|S|174|46|46.11|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | One of two Wellington stations, this was the government counterpart to the WMR Thorndon station and was the terminus of the Wairarapa Line prior to the opening of the combined Wellington station in 1937.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|0.00|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Wellington}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|16|43|S|174|46|51|E|region:NZ-WGN_type:railwaystation}}\n| [[:File:WellingtonRailwayStation 14May2003 JChristianson.jpg|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station became the combined terminus for both the North Island Main Trunk and the Wairarapa Line when it opened in 1937.\n|-\n| {{n/a}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Pipitea Point|redlink=no}}\n|\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This was Wellington's first railway station and operated from 1874 to 1884.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|2.55|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Kaiwharawhara}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|15|36.18|S|174|47|28.92|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Kaiwharawhara railway station 02.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | Both the North Island Main Trunk and Wairarapa Line are served by this station which opened in 1874.\n\nKaiwharawhara Station was closed suddenly in June 2013 as it was discovered how badly corroded the overbridge was.  In November 2013, the GWRC voted to close it permanently as on health and safety grounds, it was too expensive and nearly impossible to upgrade the station to provide step free access via ramps for disabled passengers.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|4.80|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Ngauranga}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|14|55.20|S|174|48|48.88|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Ngauranga railway station 04.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | Ngauranga was opened at the same time as Kaiwharawhara and is one of the oldest stations on the line. It was moved from its original site in 1965 due to harbour reclamations and line deviations built during the 20th century.\n|-\n| colspan=5 | Wellington did have another railway station, [[Thorndon railway station]], built by the [[Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company|Wellington and Manawatu Railway Company (WMR or W&MR)]], but this station did not serve the Wairarapa Line but instead the [[North Island Main Trunk|North Island Main Trunk (NIMT)]] via [[Johnsonville Branch|Johnsonville]].\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=5 |\n\n====Western Hutt Section====\nPetone \u2013 Melling, became Melling Branch 1 March 1954; Melling \u2013 Haywards, closed 28 February 1954\n|-\n! Distance from Hutt Valley Junction\n! Name\n! Location\n! Image\n! Notes\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|1.37|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Western Hutt|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|12|43.22|S|174|53|23.48|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | Originally known as Lower Hutt and located on the Wairarapa Line, it became a station on the Melling Branch in 1954. It was the terminus of the first section of railway line to open in the Wellington region, and marked the northernmost extent of double-track operations on the Western Hutt section.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|2.99|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Melling|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|12|13.12|S|174|54|18.94|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Melling railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves the suburb of Melling and was originally on the Wairarapa Line. It became the terminus of the Melling Branch in 1954. It was originally on the northern side of the Melling Link road but was moved to its present location when the branch opened.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|5.22|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Belmont|suffix=, New Zealand|redlink=no}}\n|\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the suburb of Belmont on the Wairarapa Line prior to the closure of this section.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|6.65|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Andrews|redlink=no}}\n|\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | Replaced Pitcaithly's in 1938 and closed in 1954.\n|-\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Pitcaithly's|redlink=no}}\n|\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | Became a tablet station in 1906 and was later replaced by Andrews, a short distance to the south, in 1938.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=5 |\n\n====Hutt Valley Section====\n|-\n! Distance from Wellington\n! Name\n! Location\n! Image\n! Notes\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|10.50|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Petone}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|13|19.91|S|174|52|9.89|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n| [[:File:Petone railway station 07.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves Petone, a suburb of Hutt City. It is at the junction of the Wairarapa Line with the Melling Branch.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|12.52|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Ava|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|13|10.52|S|174|53|30.06|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves the suburb of Ava, and was one of the original stations on the Hutt Valley Branch prior to it becoming part of the Wairarapa Line.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|14.37|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Woburn|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|13|14.51|S|174|54|40.22|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves the suburb of Woburn and was one of the first stations on the Hutt Valley Branch. It is located at the junction of the Gracefield Branch with the Wairarapa Line.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|15.50|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | [[Waterloo railway station, Lower Hutt|Waterloo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|12|49.77|S|174|55|15.95|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n| [[:File:Waterloo railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves Hutt City and is a major public transport interchange. It was the original terminus of the Hutt Valley Branch from 1927 to 1946.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|16.54|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Epuni}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|12.458|S|174|55.809|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Epuni Railway Station south.jpg|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves the suburb of Epuni and was opened in 1946 when the Hutt Valley Branch was extended north to Naenae.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|18.25|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Naenae|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|41|11.876|S|174|56.754|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves the su