a around Renall Street, Masterton.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|90.96|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Masterton}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|56.420|S|175|39.321|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Masterton railway station.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station serves the town of Masterton. It marks the northernmost extent of the Wellington suburban passenger network.\n|-\n| align=\"left\" colspan=5 |\n\n====North Wairarapa Section====\nClosed to passengers 1 August 1988\n|-\n! Distance from Wellington\n! Name\n! Location\n! Image\n! Notes\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|97.25|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Opaki|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|53|17.14|S|175|39|41.64|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Opaki railway station 02.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Opaki.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|103.53|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Kopuaranga|redlink=no}}\n|valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|49|57.82|S|175|39|51.18|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|[[:File:Kopuaranga railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Kopuaranga.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|110.56|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Mauriceville|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|46|45.08|S|175|42|0.42|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Mauriceville railway station 02.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Mauriceville.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|116.57|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Mangamahoe|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|43|47.70|S|175|43|31.44|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ|}}\n| [[:File:Mangamahoe railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Mangamahoe.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|126.82|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Eketahuna|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|38|58.37|S|175|42|23.46|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n| [[:File:Eketahuna railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the town of Eketahuna.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|130.18|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Newman|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|37|19.17|S|175|42|40.83|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n| [[:File:Newman railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Newman.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|137.28|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Hukanui|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|34|1.10|S|175|41|40.02|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Hukanui. Decommisned about 1977, Closed to passengers approx 1981. Station included Postoffice, Good Shed and Loading bank.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|144.82|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Mangamaire|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|30|46.65|S|175|44|47.86|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Mangamaire.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|147.91|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Konini|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|29|35.54|S|175|45|44.94|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Konini.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|154.62|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Pahiatua|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|26|42.12|S|175|48|54.42|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n| [[:File:Pahiatua railway station 04.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the town of Pahiatua.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|159.10|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Mangatainoka|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|24|49.47|S|175|51|44.60|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Mangatainoka.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|163.89|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Ngawapurua|redlink=no}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|40|22|51.52|S|175|53|38.68|E|type:railwaystation_region:NZ}}\n|\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the small settlement of Ngawapurua.\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | {{convert|171.50|km|2|abbr=on}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{NZR sl|Woodville|suffix=, New Zealand}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{coord|-40.3449|175.8676|format=dms}}\n| [[:File:Woodville railway station 01.JPG|Photo]]\n| valign=\"top\" | This station served the town of Woodville.\n|}\n\n===Private sidings===\nCurrently the only private sidings in use are Jukken Nisho at Waingawa and Fonterra at Pahiatua. The sidings remain at Taratahi but the main line points were removed around 2003 (Ravensdown Fertiliser). Lime Works at Mauriceville are also still connected to the network but are overgrown and covered with lime.  The former siding at Eurocell (Parapine) in Upper Hutt closed in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1=WILLIAMS |first1=COLIN |date=1 February 2012 |title=Eurocell site sold off |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/local-papers/upper-hutt-leader/6345145/Eurocell-site-sold-off |format= |department= |newspaper=Upper Hutt Leader |type= |location=Upper Hutt |publisher=Fairfax New Zealand |publication-date= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate=27 June 2014 |ref= }}</ref>\n\nExtensive sidings at Petone, Naenae (where the goods shed remains, in non-rail use), Taita (Unilever) and Trentham (Army) have been closed and removed. Other former sidings include one used by oil companies between Renall St and Masterton stations; disused sidings at Mauriceville and Eketahuna; the Ngauranga Industrial Siding to an abattoir in the Ngauranga Gorge; and a siding to the [[Featherston Military Camp]] north of Featherston during World War I.\n\n===Tunnels===\nNine tunnels have been constructed on the various routes of the Wairarapa Line. Of these, only three are now in use for railway purposes, and only the Wiwaka tunnel in northern Wairarapa (150m; between Mangamahoe & Eketahuna) has remained unaffected by deviations since the line opened.\n\nFive of these tunnels are now part of the Rimutaka Rail Trail: Mangaroa, Pakuratahi, Summit, Siberia and Prices. The Rimutaka Incline Railway project hopes to incorporate these tunnels into its restored railway line across the Rimutaka Ranges.\n\n====Original route====\nFrom Wellington to Woodville:\n* Cruickshanks Tunnel (120m) \n* Mangaroa Tunnel (152m)\n* Pakuratahi Tunnel (73m) \n* Summit Tunnel (584m) \n* Siberia Tunnel (108m) \n* Prices Tunnel (98m) \n* Wiwaka Tunnel (150m)\n\n====Current route====\nFrom Wellington to Woodville:\n* Maoribank Tunnel (572m)\n* [[Rimutaka Tunnel]] (8,798m)\n* Wiwaka Tunnel (150m)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Wairarapa Connection]]\n* [[Hutt Valley Line]]\n* [[Palmerston North - Gisborne Line]]\n* [[Te Aro Extension]]\n* [[Pahiatua Railcar Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book | last = Bromby | first = Robin | title = Rails that built a Nation: An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand Railways  | publisher = Grantham House | date = 2003 | location = Wellington | isbn = 1-86934-080-9  |ref=harv}} \n* {{cite book|last=Cameron|first=Walter Norman|title=A Line Of Railway: The Railway Conquest of the Rimutakas|location=Wellington|publisher=[[New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society]]|date=1976|ISBN=0908573006|ref={{sfnref|Cameron|1974}}}}\n* {{Churchman & Hurst Railways of New Zealand}} pages 151\u2013162.\n* Leitch, David and Brian Scott ''Exploring New Zealand's Ghost Railways'' 2nd ed., Wellington: Grantham House, 1998, pp.&nbsp;39\u201343.\n* Mahoney, J.D. ''Kings of the Iron Road'' Palmerston North: Dunmore Press, 1982, pp.&nbsp;81\u201388.\n* {{cite book|last1=McClare|first1=G J|last2=Thomson|first2=R G|title=Wairarapa Railway Memories|publisher=[[New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society]]|date=1995|ISBN=0-